[Analysis of the demographic indices of the developing countries of Southeast 
Asia].

[Article in Russian]

Rozov AA.

PIP: Southeast Asia, which is less than 6% of the earth's surface, has 25% of 
its population, and this population is growing rapidly. A process of 
urbanization is also occurring. The populations are very young; 40-45% are 
younger than 15 years of age, compared with 34% for the world as a whole. These 
young people are a problem for health services. The mortality rates went down in 
the 10-15 years after the collapse of the colonial system when these countries 
acquired their own public health systems. But they are still quite elevated 
compared with Western countries. The birthrates have also declined, but again 
they are much higher than in the developed capitalist countries. Because of this 
the governments of these countries have embarked on family planning programs. 
India, for instance, wants to lower the birthrate to 25/1000 by 1984. The infant 
mortality has dropped rapidly in all of these countries, but still remains very 
high in some of them (153/1000 live births in Bangladesh, for example). In the 
cities this mortality is much lower than in the villages. Overall, it is very 
high compared with the developed capitalist countries. The life expectancy in 
these countries is about 50 years, with women living slightly longer than men.

